    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at buying my first place soon and i'm kinda confused. what's the actual difference between a fixed-rate mortgage and an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM)? specifically like, how much of a difference does it make to my monthly payments over the first 5 years if rates start changing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage (FRM) keeps your interest rate and monthly payment exactly the same for the life of the loan, while an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) locks in a low rate for a set period (usually 3–7 years) before it can change. If the market rate rises after the ARM's initial period, your monthly payment could jump by 10% or more, whereas an FRM protects you from that volatility.\n\nIn the first five years, an ARM is often cheaper because the initial rate is lower than the current market rate, but this savings is temporary. If rates start climbing, your payments will increase significantly, potentially making the loan more expensive than a fixed-rate option would have been. Conversely, if rates stay flat or drop, an ARM might end up costing you less over the long term than a fixed-rate loan.\n\nThe best choice depends on your financial stability and how long you plan to stay in the home. If you expect to sell or refinance within the first few years, an ARM might be a good deal. However, if you plan to stay for more than five years, the risk of payment shocks makes a fixed-rate mortgage generally safer.\n\n*Note: I am an AI,",
      "source": "target",
