    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so with the ARM, the rate just kind of... shifts? like is there a cap on how much it can actually go up? i'm just worried about it being super unpredictable after the first few years.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, absolutely! The rate on an ARM doesn't just shift randomly; it has a strict \"cap\" that limits how much it can rise, but it also comes with a \"floor\" that prevents it from dropping too low.\n\nThink of the cap as a safety net that stops the payment from skyrocketing into the thousands, but it doesn't guarantee the payment will stay low.\n\nFor example, if your initial rate is 4%, you might be able to pay 3% for the first 5 years, but once those years are up, the rate could jump to 6% or 7% depending on the specific terms of your loan. If you're worried about the unpredictability, you might want to look at an ARM with a \"step-up\" cap, which limits the increase to a specific percentage (like 2%) rather than letting it go up by the full market difference.\n\nHowever, if you're worried about rates dropping, you might want to look at an ARM with a \"step-down\" cap, which limits the decrease to a specific percentage (like 1%) rather than letting it go down by the full market difference.\n\nUltimately, the cap is a way to manage the risk, but",
      "source": "target",
